In France, voting has traditionally been a low-technological experience: voters isolate themselves in a stall and put a paper sheet with their elected candidate in an envelope.
After officials have verified the voter's identity has been verified, the voter places the envelope in the ballot box and signs the voting document.
French electoral law codifies the approach rather strict.
Since 1988, ballots must be transparent so that voters and observers can see that there are no envelopes at the start of the vote and that no envelopes are added except those that are properly counted from the eligible for voting.
